<DOC><DOCNO> AP890802-0035 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0432EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     08-02 0357</FIRST><SECOND>PM-South Korea,0368</SECOND><HEAD>Government Detains Top Opposition Leader</HEAD><BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Security agents interrogated thecountry's top opposition leader today to determine if he knew inadvance about a lawmaker's illegal visit to North Korea.   Investigators from the Agency for National Security Planning,the government's security arm, questioned Kim Dae-jung after takinghim from his party headquarters to a downtown police station.   Police and government officials declined comment. A courtwarrant was issued allowing authorities to hold Kim for 24 hours.   The warrant said Kim, head of the Party for Peace and Democracy,would be investigated to determine whether he was involved in atrip to the communist north by Suh Kyung-won, a former Party forPeace and Democracy lawmaker.   Kim has denied involvement in Suh's trip and charged thegovernment with political harrassment.   Suh is jailed on charges of violating national security forvisiting North Korean leader Kim Il Sung in August 1988. SouthKorea bans unauthorized trips to the communist north, maintainingthat contacts with its rival must be through official channels.   Also detained today was National Assembly member Moon Dong-hwan,a senior Party for Peace and Demcracy member and brother ofdissident Presbyterian Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, who visited North Koreafor talks with North Korean leaders.   The minister also is jailed.   Hundreds of party members and supporters chanted Kim's name andanti-government slogans when agents arrived at party headquartersand presented detention orders to Kim and Moon before taking themaway.   ``Disband the NSP (national security agency)!'' they shouted.The opposition leader smiled and waved as he left.   Party spokesman Lee Sang-soo said ``the national securityagency's scheme to suppress and destroy the party has reached theextreme'' with Kim's detention.   Suh turned himself into authorities June 25 and was formallyarrested three days later. Party leaders said they encouraged Suhto turn himself in after the party belatedly heard about the trip.   Kim ran unsuccessfully for the presidency in December 1987,splitting the opposition vote with rival opposition leader KimYoung-sam. President Roh Tae-woo, a former army general, received36.6 percent of the vote.</TEXT></DOC>